        <outline text="Academic">
            <outline text="MAEVA: A Framework for Security Risk Response Based on Attack-Motivation Analysis">
                <outline text="Motivation #slide ">
                    <outline text="Organisations are increasingly facing cyber attacks, targeting their systems and data"/>
                    <outline text="Security assessment and risk analysis are popular techniques for informing budget spending in relation to security controls"/>
                    <outline text="They mainly focus on analysing the expected impact of an attack on the organisation's assets"/>
                    <outline text="However, this is a difficult task and tricky to get accurate estimates."/>
                    <outline text="Could there be new methodologies, focusing on &quot;the other side&quot;, i.e. the motivation that an external attack might have on launching attacks?"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Research Contributions #slide ">
                    <outline text="This paper presents two contributions.">
                        <outline text="The first contribution is a novel framework for risk assessment of cyber security attacks on an organisation."/>
                        <outline text="The second contribution is an application of this framework to game-theoretic risk assessment."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The main difference to previous work is:">
                        <outline text="The novel framework, entitled MAEVA, focuses on the attackers perspective (rather than the defender, i.e. the security assessor)"/>
                        <outline text="We develop a scheme, entitled the Attack Incentive Matrix (AIM), which can be contrasted with the standard Risk Response Matrix"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Benefits arise when using this framework in combination with traditional approaches, as it might increase accuracy of risk estimates"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="The Challenges of Risk Computation #slide ">
                    <outline text="Using formal notation, the risk $$R$$ can be expressed as an expected impact $$I$$."/>
                    <outline text="This can be computed using the following equation:">
                        <outline text="$$R = p \cdot I. $$$$ #label:RiskEq"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Here $$p$$ is the probability of an attack occurring, often referred to as {\em attack likelihood}."/>
                    <outline text="From this equation, one can see that the problem now is to quantify and compute $$p$$ and $$I$$ and the difficulty is to perform a realistic estimate of these variables."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Risk Assessment Based on Risk Response Matrix #slide ">
                    <outline text="It is now assumed that one is able to determine the attack likelihood $$p$$."/>
                    <outline text="This leads to a table containing risk response actions, such as defending critical assets, recovering from an attack, planning for defense or choosing not to respond at all."/>
                    <outline text="An appropriate response action is then determined by indexing the table rows with attack probabilities using qualitative metrics (low, medium or high) and its columns with a measure for the impact (minor, moderate or major) of the attack."/>
                    <outline text="This table is referred to as {\em Risk Response Matrix} (RRM) in this talk."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Risk Response Matrix #slide ">
                    <outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/tCVcb1pC3e_cGA0BlV8lNWTP) "/>
                    <outline text="\begin{figure}[ht]{"/>
                    <outline text="\centering"/>
                    <outline text="\includegraphics[width=0.5 \textwidth]{Figures/RRM}"/>
                    <outline text="}"/>
                    <outline text="\caption{Risk Response Matrix (RRM) [NIST]}"/>
                    <outline text="\label{RiskResponseMatrixDefender}"/>
                    <outline text="\end{figure}"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="The MAEVA Framework (Explanation) #slide ">
                    <outline text="\textbf{M}otive: the underlying reason for attacking the victim. This could be for the purposes of financial gains, or personal satisfaction."/>
                    <outline text="\textbf{A}bility: the capability of the attacker to invest in resources for implementing the attack, as well as her/his technical knowledge"/>
                    <outline text="\textbf{E}xploitability: the ease by which the system can be penetrated, through exploiting a vulnerability."/>
                    <outline text="\textbf{V}isibility of target: how prominent is the target -- e.g.~does it have a popular website or brand name, or a large user base?"/>
                    <outline text="\textbf{A}ttractiveness of target: from the point of view of the attacker, how attractive is the target?"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="The MAEVA Framework -- Attack Incentive Matrix #slide">
                    <outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/P5zY4iNxRQgamTDyG0X0rylj) "/>
                    <outline text="\begin{figure}[ht]"/>
                    <outline text="\centering"/>
                    <outline text="\includegraphics[width=0.8 \textwidth]{Figures/AIM}"/>
                    <outline text="\caption{Attack Incentive Matrix (AIM)}"/>
                    <outline text="\label{AttackIncentiveMatrixAttacker}"/>
                    <outline text="\end{figure}"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Game Theory -- Introducing Basic Terminology #slide ">
                    <outline text="Game theory is &quot;__the study of mathematical models of conflict and cooperation between intelligent rational decision-makers.__&quot; "/>
                    <outline text=" ![Pasted image](https://dynalist.io/u/7vAmM06TbPR5kvA4MVEhQnAD) "/>
                    <outline text="Important Aspects:">
                        <outline text="Game Type"/>
                        <outline text="Players"/>
                        <outline text="Utilities (payoffs)"/>
                        <outline text="Strategies"/>
                        <outline text="Solving (optimal strategies)"/>
                        <outline text="Nash Equilibrium"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Application to Game Theoretic Risk Assessment #slide ">
                    <outline text="Under the assumption of complete information about the strategies available to both players, the use of game theory improves the traditional risk assessment.">
                        <outline text="Standard RA: the risk response matrix gives a deterministic response action (strategy sd)"/>
                        <outline text="Game Theory: we are using a mixed equilibrium strategy (probabilistic) which guarantee expected utility u*"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The security game $$\mathcal{G}$$ between the attacker and defender in strategic normal form:"/>
                    <outline text="\begin{table}[h] \centering\caption{Payoff Matrix for $$\mathcal{G}(\mathcal{D},\mathcal{A})$$ }\label{PayoffMatrix}"/>
                    <outline text="$$\begin{array}{|c|c|c|}\hline \mathcal{D} \downarrow \mathcal{A} \rightarrow &amp; s_a &amp; s_{-a} \\ \hline s_{d}  &amp; -c_{\mathcal{D}}, -c_{\mathcal{A}} &amp; -c_{\mathcal{D}}, 0      \\ \hline s_{-d} &amp; -I , G- c_{\mathcal{A}} &amp; 0, 0 \\ \hline\end{array} $$"/>
                    <outline text="\end{table}"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Using MAEVA to Inform Game Payoff Functions #slide ">
                    <outline text="Before the game can be solved, it needs to be specified in terms of the precise values for the payoff functions, and Table \ref{PayoffMatrix} reveals that the MAEVA framework can be used to determine (an estimate for) $$G$$."/>
                    <outline text="The parameter $$c_{\mathcal{D}}$$ is effectively the {\em defense budget} of the organisation and $$c_{\mathcal{A}}$$ can be related to the attacker's effort $$e$$."/>
                    <outline text="Hence, in a natural way, both the RRM and AIM methodologies provide the input parameters for the game."/>
                    <outline text="The analysis of the game based on computing the Nash equilibrium will then result in the desired risk value."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Summary #slide">
                    <outline text="The MAEVA framework is based on analysing the incentive an adversary may have to attack the organisation when weighing up the potential gain from the attack and the effort it takes to breach the system."/>
                    <outline text="We argue that this point of view, which is fundamentally different to that taken in traditional risk assessment, can complement and enhance the standard approach based on estimating risk as a function of attack likelihood and impact on the organisation."/>
                    <outline text="Our framework is very convenient when wishing to inform the design of complete information games, modelling attacker-defender scenarios."/>
                    <outline text="It is a natural first step an organisation can take to prepare a game-theoretic risk assessment."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Conclusion #slide ">
                    <outline text="To our knowledge, our framework constitutes a novel approach and we recommend using it as a practical methodology for any organisation wishing to assess risk, perhaps in combination with other mainstream methods."/>
                    <outline text="The next step for this research would be an implementation of a real scenario, and a detailed evaluative comparison with existing approaches."/>
                    <outline text="For example, an organisation could review their information assets, apply both the RRM and AIM, and compare the resulting parameters."/>
                    <outline text="It would be interesting to relate this to historical information about cyber security incidents that happened in the past at this organisation, or in its sector."/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="CyBOK">
                <outline text="Background #slide ">
                    <outline text="The Cyber Security Body of Knowledge (CyBOK) specifies Cyber Security Knowledge relevant in the professional and educational domain. "/>
                    <outline text="In the UK, the NCSC Certified Degree Scheme is now based on using the CyBOK for universities to demonstrate focus, breadth, and depth of a cyber curriculum. "/>
                    <outline text="A mapping framework exists to help identify CyBOK Knowledge Areas containing specific keywords and to understand their contextual structure."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Aims &amp;amp; Objectives #slide ">
                    <outline text="This project aims to provide a novel mapping framework for the CyBOK based on a web-based searchable representation of CyBOK Knowledge Trees and, to deliver a tool to export mapping information into a range of document formats. "/>
                    <outline text="In addition to being intuitive and user-friendly, the proposed framework seeks to enrich the mapping tasks with an alternative visualisation, using mind maps.  "/>
                    <outline text="Three objectives are proposed:">
                        <outline text="1. To convert the CyBOK Knowledge Trees to a single online hierarchical outline, hosted on the Dynalist website [4]."/>
                        <outline text="2. To create an export tool, converting mapping-related search queries into a range of standard text-based formats."/>
                        <outline text="3. To provide a companion website, cross-referencing the online CyBOK and providing additional documentation with alternative visualisations of the CyBOK."/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Demo #slide "/>
                <outline text="Strategic Benefits #slide ">
                    <outline text="The provision of an alternative way to visualise, search and interact with the CyBOK will reduce the learning curve of understanding its Knowledge Areas, hence encouraging their use. "/>
                    <outline text="The proposed tool simplifies granular mapping processes through keyword-based search results and includes convenient export functions to multiple formats. "/>
                    <outline text="Ultimately this may lead to greater adoption of the CyBOK and improved-quality cyber programmes in the UK and internationally."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="References #slide ">
                    <outline text="[1] Kingston University, Network and Information Security MSc Course Page, Retrieved from [https://www.kingston.ac.uk/postgraduate/courses/network-information-security-msc/](https://www.kingston.ac.uk/postgraduate/courses/network-information-security-msc/), 2020"/>
                    <outline text="[2] E. Pfluegel, N. Bailey, J. Denholm-Price, Using Zoomable Online Outliners in  STEM Education, 4th Horizons in STEM Conference, Kingston, July 2019"/>
                    <outline text="[3] E. Pfluegel, Exploration and Visualisation of Security Knowledge for Certified Degrees: Selected Use Cases for Educators and Students, Talk at Inaugural CISSE UK Workshop Meeting, July 2019"/>
                    <outline text="[4] Dynalist Inc, Dynalist Outliner Homepage, Retrieved from https://dynalist.io/, 2020"/>
