                <outline text="Motivation #h1  #eyo-style:Section ">
                    <outline text="Case Study 1 #slide ">
                        <outline text="__According to [omnicoreagency.com](https://www.omnicoreagency.com/youtube-statistics/), there are currently more than 31 million YouTube channels. Every year, thousands of them are compromised or receive unsolicited, misleading or illegal comments. Rather than purely relying on the account owners to spot and report these incidents, YouTube is employing dedicated staff to periodically screen randomly selected channels. Unfortunately, this screening process is time-consuming, staff need to be appropriately trained and might also need counselling. Hence, the question arises whether a strategy could be devised in order to replace the random selection process by a more informed one, taking into account the attacker's motivation.__ #eyo-style:Normal "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Case Study 2 #slide ">
                        <outline text="Alan is in charge of vulnerability management for the IT systems of his company. The security policy of his organisation only allows for critical patching of one software per day, due to issues with bandwidth and system downtime during the patching process. He has identified two different vulnerabilities that require patching. He downloads their CVSS scores but finds that they are very similar, making it difficult to decide on a priority ranking. He would like to use some information contained in some CVSS subscores in such a way that he follows game-theoretic principles, taking into account both the attacker's capabilities and the impact on the system. This would give him a different view and could potentially lead to a clearer prioritisation."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Case Study 2 #slide  #wfe-ignore-outline ">
                        <outline text="__An organisation requires employees to report cyber security incidents such as receiving spam emails, phishing attacks or attempts to be socially engineered. Employees are generally cooperative and willing to be involved, but find it difficult to report these incidents due to a high workload of their day-to-day tasks. The company decides to request monthly reports, in order to force the employees to send their security reports. As a consequence, some employees become lazy and do not fully divulge the extend of occurring incidents. Hence, the company would like to find a criterion for whether they can trust a received report or not, by taking into account possible motivations of its sender.__ #eyo-style:Normal "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Approach Using Game Theory #slide ">
                        <outline text="We would like to use the mathematical concept of game theory in order to address the previous two case studies."/>
                        <outline text="The usefulness of this approach depends on:">
                            <outline text="The level of sophistication of the specific game model;"/>
                            <outline text="The required assumptions that need to be made for the model to be valid;"/>
                            <outline text="The acceptance of the game theoretic model by the real-world players."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="GAME THEORY" _note="https://dynalist.io/d/gcskC8EanDTKsGE-U8yP7HPC#z=cdU7FseL1kfr0iYksOXArpN8"/>
                <outline text="SECURITY GAMES" _note="https://dynalist.io/d/gcskC8EanDTKsGE-U8yP7HPC#z=sxPhzllEsvBXreyV5gANFrmj&amp;q=%23slide%20"/>
                <outline text="ISSUE"/>
                <outline text="Conclusion #h ">
                    <outline text="Summary #slide ">
                        <outline text="In this talk, we have outlined some recent game-theoretical applications to security scenarios."/>
                        <outline text="We have explored the use of massive security games for optimal allocation of resources."/>
                        <outline text="We have also analysed a strategic security game in order to inform vulnerability patching with game theory."/>
                        <outline text="The usefulness of game theory depends on its acceptance amongst practitioners, including both defender and attacker."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Outlook #slide ">
                        <outline text="Higher-dimensional matrix models for more realistic dilemma analysis and security scenario modelling need to be mastered:">
                            <outline text="Focus on order $n=3$ first, then tackle higher orders."/>
                            <outline text="Building on complete information games, devise incomplete information game models."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The use of game-theoretic models in security standards would be an ultimate achievement:">
                            <outline text="Security management and assessment (OCTAVE, NIST RMF, ISO-27000),"/>
                            <outline text="Vulnerability scoring and assessment (CVSS)."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
