                        <outline text="A HaaS Game  #eyo-style:Subsection ">
                            <outline text="Planned Contributions #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="First GT model of HaaS"/>
<outline text="Based on expanding previous work on Sensor Games, taking into account a rich motivation profile of human sensor node"/>
<outline text="Formulation of Reference Game"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="HaaS Scenario -- Analysis #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="Players">
    <outline text="Human Sensor $$H$$ ($$S$$ in reference game)"/>
    <outline text="Report Receiving Organisation $$R$$ ($$R$$ in reference game)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="We elicit the following motivations for actions that $$H$$ might undertake:">
    <outline text="malicious or"/>
    <outline text="honest and">
        <outline text="reliable (accurate) or"/>
        <outline text="unreliable (inaccurate), either knowingly (lazy, negligent) or unknowingly (socially engineered)"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Assumptions #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="Laziness implies maliciousness"/>
<outline text="The honest human sensor will always cooperate, so has no choice of actions per se">
    <outline text="But honesty does not always imply correctness "/>
    <outline text="We want to model the fact that they could unknowingly create false reports"/>
    <outline text="The perceived correct report might not be accurate as the human sensor might have a vulnerability (socially engineered, forgetful, negligent)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Lack of information -- Summary">
    <outline text="The report receiver does not know whether the human sensor is honest or malicious (type)"/>
    <outline text="An honest human sensor does not know whether she is reliable or not, or socially engineered (stochastic element)"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="HaaS Sensor Types #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="Type 1: uncooperative (internal attacker)">
    <outline text="malicious -- reduce security of organisation">
        <outline text="disgruntled (seeking emotional reward), "/>
        <outline text="greedy (seeking financial reward)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="knowingly/deliberately unreliable (inaccurate) -- apply minimal effort in contribution to overall security ">
        <outline text="lazy (give it low priority, too focused on other job aspects)"/>
        <outline text="negligent (personal weak discipline) ?"/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Type 2: cooperative but unknowingly unreliable (inaccurate), ">
    <outline text="not cyberwise and socially engineered (externally attacked)"/>
    <outline text="misconception of own cyber skills"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Type 3: cooperative and reliable (accurate) -- increase security"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="INBOX #wfe-ignore-outline ">
                            <outline text="Strategies #slide " complete="true">
<outline text="Report receiver $$\mathcal{R}$$ has two pure strategies $$s^\mathcal{R}\in \{t_r,\overline{t}_r\}$$ : ">
    <outline text="$$t_r$$ -- to trust the received report (and to benefit from its content to improve national security)"/>
    <outline text="$$\overline{t}_r$$ -- to not trust (to prevent damage, either by recognising the reporting node as malicious or as negligent)"/>
</outline>
<outline text="Human sensor $$\mathcal{H}$$ has three pure strategies $$s^\mathcal{H}\in \{c, a, n\}$$:">
    <outline text="$$c$$ -- cooperate and to send the perceived correct report (and to benefit from increased esteem, or being paid a bounty)"/>
    <outline text="$$a$$ -- perform an attack by giving misleading reports (in order to get a psychological &quot;kick&quot; or some other financial reward from a cyber criminal)"/>
    <outline text="$$n$$ -- not sending a report at all (as too lazy and preferring to &quot;get on with the job&quot;)"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Complete Versus Incomplete Information #slide ">
<outline text="Public information, known to all players">
    <outline text="Specific game theoretic model, comprising of game type and payoff  functions, including solution algorithm "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Private information">
    <outline text="Report receiver">
        <outline text="Can use statistics to">
            <outline text="Estimate reliability of human sensor $$p_{\mathcal{R}}$$"/>
            <outline text="Compute expected frequency of reportable cyber incidents $$p_{F}$$"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Unknown information ">
            <outline text="Types -- whether human sensor is malicious $$p_{M}$$ or honest $$p_{H}$$"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Human sensor:">
        <outline text="Knows whether malicious or not"/>
        <outline text="Could get feedback to know whether reliable or not (useful for training purposes)"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Likelihood of attack on reporting channel is not known by anyone "/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Reports #slide ">
<outline text="Notation: $$r$$ -- a report"/>
<outline text="Could report incident only, or also absence"/>
<outline text="Could be externally attacked (modified, delayed or fabricated)"/>
<outline text="Could be synchronous or asynchronous"/>
<outline text="Examples">
    <outline text="&quot;Have received a spam email at 8:10h, which was not detected by the spam filter&quot;"/>
    <outline text="&quot;Have discovered a freeware website that contains links to some malware&quot;"/>
    <outline text="&quot;Within the last seven days of the reporting period, there were three replies on the company's Twitter feed with external links that appear to expose confidential information&quot;"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Malicious Human Sensor Game #slide ">
<outline text="The malicious reporter sends a fake report"/>
<outline text="She can also decide to deceive the recipient, by sending a correct report"/>
<outline text="Generally, she will try to optimise the rewards from the attack or deception versus potential punishment such as loss of reputation or prosecution"/>
<outline text="This can be modelled as an IDS game where the defence action of the report receiver is to not trust the report"/>
                            </outline>
