                <outline text="Part II -- Solving It #eyo-style:Section ">
                    <outline text="INBOX - NE ANALYSIS #wfe-ignore-outline ">
                        <outline text="Game 1 -- cont. #slide ">
                            <outline text="Strategies">
<outline text="Strategies:">
    <outline text="$$S_{SP} = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)$$"/>
    <outline text="$$S_A = (R_1, R_2, \ldots, R_N)$$"/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Analysis of Game">
<outline text="Static complete information parametric normal form game"/>
<outline text="There is no pure strategy Nash equilibrium"/>
<outline text="They compute the mixed Nash equilibrium for the cases $$N = 2$$ and the general case for the assumption that the attacker only chooses one resource to attack."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Game Analysis #slide ">
                            <outline text="Result: conditions under which a pure strategy BNE exists for the signalling game"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Bayesian Nash Equilibrium (BNE) #slide ">
                            <outline text="Non-Bayesian game: strategy profile is a NE iff every strategy in that profile is a best response to every other strategy"/>
                            <outline text="Bayesian Games: Players maximise their expected payoffs">
<outline text="__Pooling Equilibrium__: if the first player sends the same signal, regardless of his type."/>
<outline text="__Separating Equilibrium__: if the first player sends different signals, depending on his type."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Conclusion #slide #wfe-ignore-outline "/>
            </outline>
            <outline text="ICITST Talk" _note="#title #h #slide &#xA;[WorkFlowy  Mirror](https://workflowy.com/#/088dff66f431)&#xA;https://www.dropbox.com/s/t4dfv79gb8z6jc0/ICITST%20Talk%20-%20Talks%20-%20Dynalist.pdf?dl=0">
                <outline text="A Multi-Channel Steganographic Protocol for Secure SMS Mobile Banking #title"/>
                <outline text="Introduction #h">
                    <outline text="Background #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="Online banking is a huge success story"/>
                        <outline text="In 2014, there were 133.5 million digital banking users in the U.S. and this figure was projected to increase to 161.6 million in 2019"/>
                        <outline text="Mobile banking is increasingly the most preferred online banking approach"/>
                        <outline text="SMS banking is an attractive solution due to its simplicity and cost-effectiveness "/>
                        <outline text="However there are concerns about the security "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="SMS Banking Security #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="However the following security attacks might take place:">
                            <outline text="An unauthorised external entity (adversary) performing passive or active attacks:">
<outline text="Eavesdropping "/>
<outline text="Man-in-the-middle attack"/>
<outline text="Replay attack"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The government and/or the mobile service provider eavesdropping on the communication, or modifying message content"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="How could we design a secure SMS mobile banking protocol?"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Scenario #slide" complete="true">
                        <outline text="We consider the following scenario: ">
                            <outline text="Amara wants to implement secure SMS banking in order to pay money into Ebere's account"/>
                            <outline text="However, she is in an insecure and poor infrastructure area, were there is no internet connection in peoples' homes, "/>
                            <outline text="She has a (dual sim) mobile phone which is however a low powered device (not connected to the internet)"/>
                            <outline text="On the other hand, there are public cybercafes in the neighbourhood town"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Security Assumptions #slide" complete="true">
                        <outline text="The bank can be trusted"/>
                        <outline text="The cybercafe, government and/or the mobile operator(s) cannot">
                            <outline text="They could carry out passive or active attacks (evesdropping, man-in-the-middle, steganalysis) "/>
                            <outline text="Attacks could be done on their own, or by working together (collaborative attack)"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Our Approach: The Protocol #h">
                    <outline text="Main Idea #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="We want to avoid encryption, as it attracts suspicion due to the socially constrained SMS channel"/>
                        <outline text="Instead, we use a combination of low-entropy and high-entropy steganography"/>
                        <outline text="The use of three communication channels further increases attack resistance"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Previous Work #slide" complete="true">
                        <outline text="Our work was inspired by">
                            <outline text="Beato, F. (2015). Private Information Sharing in Online Communities."/>
                            <outline text="Beato, F., \&amp; Rasmussen, K. B. (2014). Undetectable Communication: The Online Social Networks Case. PST 2014"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="It is a suitable specialisation and application to novel domain of">
                            <outline text="Clarke, Charles A and Pfluegel, Eckhard and Tsaptsinos, D. (2015). Multi-channel overlay protocols: Implementing ad-hoc message authentication in social media platforms. CyberSA 2015"/>
                            <outline text="Clarke, C. A. (2016). Dual Carrier Steganographic Messaging Protocols for Mobile Messaging Applications. PhD Thesis, Kingston University"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Notations #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="Let Amara be a sender wanting to transfer money to Ebere's account through her bank"/>
                        <outline text="Let $$m$$ be the corresponding SMS message"/>
                        <outline text="We additionally denote $$m_1$$, $$m_2$$ faked, unsuspicious SMS messages "/>
                        <outline text="Let $$E$$ and $$D$$ be high-entropy steganographic encoding (hiding) and decoding functions"/>
                        <outline text="Let $$b$$ be a binary value to be hidden in $$m_3$$, a stego object (e.g. image for LSB hiding)"/>
                        <outline text="Let $$C_1$$ and $$C_2$$ be two separate wireless (2g or 3g) channels"/>
                        <outline text="Finally, $$C_3$$ denotes an insecure internet channel"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Description #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="Amara creates the SMS banking instruction message $$m$$. "/>
                        <outline text="She also generates two fake unsuspicious banking instructions $$m_1$$ and $$m_2$$."/>
                        <outline text="Then, $$m_1$$ and $$m_2$$ are transmitted to the bank over two independent mobile wireless channels $$C_1$$ and $$C_2$$ respectively."/>
                        <outline text="Amara computes  $$b=m \oplus m_1\oplus m_2$$."/>
                        <outline text="The binary value $$b$$ is covertly embedded using an LSB hiding map, resulting in $$m_3$$."/>
                        <outline text="Finally $$m_3$$ is sent to the bank as web form data, using HTTP POST."/>
                        <outline text="On receiving $$m_3$$ and extracting $$b$$, the bank can recover $$m$$ by computing $$b \oplus m_1\oplus m_2$$."/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Architecture #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="![](https://www.dropbox.com/s/5s6fdz7m0ugqe22/Screenshot%202017-12-08%2016.17.24.png?dl=1) #wfe-style-none"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Example #slide" complete="true">
                        <outline text="Amara's SMS banking instruction: $$m=$$ &quot;Transfer £500 to Ms Ebere&quot;"/>
                        <outline text="First fake SMS message: $$m_1 = $$ &quot;Transfer £100 to Mr Nmachi&quot;"/>
                        <outline text="Second fake SMS message: $$m_2 =$$ &quot;Send me my current bank statement&quot;"/>
                        <outline text="Third message in HTTP POST request: $$m_3=E(b)$$ where">
                            <outline text="$$b=m \oplus m_1 \oplus m_2$$"/>
                            <outline text="This is 53656E6420391715716B28756137C2E699E7217225213F0220195239417D61111B"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Bank reconstructs $$m=b \oplus m_1 \oplus m_2$$"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Security Analysis #h">
                    <outline text="Adversaries #slide " complete="true">
                        <outline text="External SMS Interceptor"/>
                        <outline text="Mobile Operators I and II">
                            <outline text="Malicious Employee"/>
                            <outline text="Management"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Cybercafé ">
                            <outline text="Negligent Owner"/>
                            <outline text="Malicious Cybercafé User"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="ISP of Cybercafé "/>
                        <outline text="Government"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Results #slide "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Conclusion #h">
                    <outline text="Conclusion #slide" complete="true">
                        <outline text="We have designed a secure SMS banking protocol with distinct novel features: ">
                            <outline text="The protocol employs three channels"/>
                            <outline text="It is based on a hybrid steganography model"/>
                            <outline text="It provides security against a range of adversaries, in particular the mobile operators"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="We are working towards a robust design and implementation for real-world use"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
        <outline text="INBOX">
            <outline text="First Attempt: One-Channel?">
                <outline text="Let us disregard the standard use of &quot;secure&quot; SMS">
                    <outline text="This is **__not__** end-to-end secure as the mobile operator (who normally acts as a trusted service provider/third party) can easily get hold of the key"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Symmetric Encryption Approach #slide ">
                    <outline text="Illustration  \[\begin{array} {c c c c}  \\Alice &amp;amp;  &amp;amp; Bank \\  c=E_K(m) &amp;amp; \xrightarrow[\text{c}]{mobile\,operator} &amp;amp; m=D_K(c) \\  \end{array}\]"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Security Analysis #slide ">
                    <outline text="Key needs to be stored securely."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Problem: The symmetric key needs to be exchanged securely with the bank prior to actually running this protocol"/>
                <outline text="Alternatives?"/>
                <outline text="Asymmetric Encryption #slide ">
                    <outline text="Illustration  \[\begin{array} {c c c c}  \\Alice &amp;amp;  &amp;amp; Bank \\  c=E{_P}{_k}(m) &amp;amp; \xrightarrow[\text{$$Pk$$}|{c}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator$$}}&amp;amp; m=D{_P}{_k}(c) \\ \end{array}\]"/>
                    <outline text="Alice generates two keys $$Pk$$ (public key) and $$Sk$$ (private key)."/>
                    <outline text="The $$Pk$$ is used to encrypt the SMS cipher text, while the $$Sk$$ will be used to decrypt the message."/>
                    <outline text="However, this would require a trusted third party such as a key distribution centre to distribute the private keys to any party that wishes to communicate."/>
                    <outline text="Slower than symmetric key encryption."/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Second Attempt: Two-Channel Encryption Approach">
                <outline text="A secure architecture and protocol can be achieved where multiple channels or carriers are utilized.">
                    <outline text="The concept of a protocol, were a dual sim phone is used as a secure steganographic carrier for SMS banking."/>
                    <outline text="One sim can be used as a first carrier while the second sim can be used as the second carrier."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Main idea #slide ">
                    <outline text="We have a dual sim phone"/>
                    <outline text="One sim can be used as a first carrier while the second sim can be used as the second carrier."/>
                    <outline text="As a secure steganographic carrier for SMS banking. "/>
                    <outline text="Alice wants to pay in money into Bob's account"/>
                    <outline text="How could we then secure our communication?"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Symmetric Encryption Approach #slide">
                    <outline text="Illustration #slide ">
                        <outline text="\[\begin{array}{c c c c} Alice &amp;amp; &amp;amp; Bank\\  E_K(m)=c &amp;amp; \xrightarrow[\text{SIM 1$$(carrier\,1)$$ $$\, \, \, \,c$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,1\,(channel\,1)$$}} &amp;amp; \\ \\&amp;amp;\xrightarrow[\text{$$SIM$$$$\,$$$$2$$$$\,(carier\,2)$$$$\, \, \, \,K$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,2$$$$\,$$(channel$$\,$$2)$$$$}} &amp;amp; D_k(c)=m \\  \end{array}\]"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Security Analysis #slide ">
                    <outline text="The two carriers should be considered adversarial to each other. This will potentially prevent information leakage and attacks.  "/>
                    <outline text="This could be secure against certain attacks"/>
                    <outline text="Is it possible to eavesdrop and intercept on communication?"/>
                    <outline text="With advance cryptanalysis systems, this could be broken."/>
                    <outline text="**How can we secure our communication, if there is a probability that the government and mobile operator could eavesdrop and intercept our transactions?**"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Asymmetric Encryption Approach #slide ">
                    <outline text="Illustration ">
                        <outline text="\[\begin{array}{c c c c} Alice &amp;amp; &amp;amp; Bank\\  c=E{_P}{_k}(m) &amp;amp; \xrightarrow[\text{SIM 1$$(carrier\,1)$$ $$\, \, \, \,{Pk}\parallel c$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,1\,(channel\,1)$$}} &amp;amp; \\ \\&amp;amp;\xrightarrow[\text{$$SIM$$$$\,$$$$2$$$$\,(carier\,2)$$$$\, \, \, \,{Sk}$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,2$$$$\,$$(channel$$\,$$2)$$$$}} &amp;amp; m=D{_S}{_k}(c) \\  \end{array}\]"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Yet Another Idea with 2 channels #slide ">
                    <outline text="Asymmetric Encryption Approach">
                        <outline text="Alice has a secret $$s$$ $$\in$$ S and uses a ($$a$$, $$n$$ threshold scheme) to share the secret between her and the bank. The secret $$s$$ could be secret key $$Sk$$ $$\in$$ $$K$$ or a ciphertext $$c$$ $$\in$$ $$C$$"/>
                        <outline text="Illustration ">
                            <outline text="\[\begin{array}{c c c c} Alice &amp;amp; &amp;amp; Bank\\  c=E{_P}{_k}(m) &amp;amp; \xrightarrow[\text{SIM 1$$(carrier\,1)$$ $$\, \, \, \,{Pk}\parallel c$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,1\,(channel\,1)$$}} &amp;amp; \\ \\&amp;amp;\xrightarrow[\text{$$SIM$$$$\,$$$$2$$$$\,(carier\,2)$$$$\, \, \, \,{Sk}$$}]{\text{$$mobile$$$$\,$$$$operator\,2$$$$\,$$(channel$$\,$$2)$$$$}} &amp;amp; m=D{_S}{_k}(c) \\  \end{array}\]">
<outline text="The secret key $${S}{k}$$ $$\in$$ K could be divided into to $$n$$ parts, hashed and shared without a trusted third party.">
    <outline text="Alice divide the secret key $$Sk$$ into $$n$$ pieces $$Sk_1$$, $$Sk_2$$....., $$Sk_n$$ in a way such that:">
        <outline text="Knowledge of any $$a$$ or more $$Sk_1$$ pieces makes $$Sk$$ easily computable;"/>
        <outline text="Knowledge of any $$a$$ $$-$$ $$1$$ or fewer $$Sk_1$$ pieces leaves $$Sk$$ completely undermined."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="With the key divided into the following pieces"/>
    <outline text=" $$Sk_1$$, $$Sk_2$$....., $$Sk_n$$ $$\longmapsto$$ $$H(k_1)= h_1$$, $$H(k_2)= h_2$$,.......$$H(k_n)= h_n$$."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The cipher text $$c$$ $$\in$$ $$C$$ could be divided into to parts, hashed and shared without a trusted third party.">
    <outline text="$$c_1$$, $$c_2$$, ..........$$c_n$$. $$\longmapsto$$ $$H(c_1)= h_1$$, $$H(c_2)= h_2$$,........$$H(c_n)= h_n$$"/>
</outline>
<outline text="However, in this scenario, the secret $$s$$ needs to be shared a trusted authority."/>
<outline text="We assume that the secret $$s$$ could be recovered, if government corrupts or collaborates with at least $$a+1$$ participants (mobile operator and other trusted authorities)."/>
<outline text="The secret $$Sk$$ or $$c$$ needs to be shared without a trusted third-party. "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
            </outline>
            <outline text="Related Work/Issues">
                <outline text="Should we trust trusted third parties [in general]? ">
                    <outline text="When the infrastructure of a trusted CA is breached the whole chain of trust is broken. E.g. The 2011 incident at CA DigiNotar broke the trust of the Dutch governments PKI."/>
                    <outline text="As Bruce Schneier has pointed out, after the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures, no third party should in fact ever be trusted. https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2013/12/nsa_spying_who.html       https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2014/02/who_should_stor.html"/>
                    <outline text="Problems with Integrity and No repudation"/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Suppose two parties share a secure private key ">
                    <outline text="What if the mobile operator or government have the capacity to decrypt a strong encryption."/>
                    <outline text="According to Bruce Schneier the NSA is able to decrypt most of the Internet. They're doing it primarily by cheating, not by mathematics. https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2013/09/the_nsa_is_brea.html"/>
                </outline>
            </outline>
        </outline>
